2026-04-16 12:15:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=["Control Module 3: internal connection from input positive conductor to switch (port 'n')"] hypothesis_explanation="Tracing the series path shows ~12 V is present from the PSU through Control Modules 1 and 2 and at the input of Control Module 3. The first point where the differential voltage across the two conductors collapses to ~0 V is across Control Module 3, and all downstream modules see 0 V. Detailed probing of Control Module 3 reveals that its input positive cable indeed has ~12 V, but the internal node (port 'n') where this conductor should be connected to the switch and the rest of the module is floating/disconnected; the switch, LED, resistor, and outgoing conductor sit near 0 V. This indicates an internal open circuit between the positive input terminal and the internal switch/through-path, not a polarity error or external cabling issue. Repairing or replacing Control Module 3 (specifically restoring continuity from its positive input terminal to the switch/through conductor) should restore 12 V to the rest of the chain and allow the lamp and downstream indicators to operate, assuming no further faults."
